com.avaya.csta.binding

Class RegisterTerminalRequest

  • java.lang.Object
    • ch.ecma.csta.CastorObject
      • com.avaya.csta.binding.RegisterTerminalRequest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class RegisterTerminalRequest
extends ch.ecma.csta.CastorObject
implements java.io.Serializable
    Used to register a terminal for Avaya switches. Registers a specific device with Communication Manager in order to gain access to the signalling and possibly the media of a phone or extension.

    If registering with DependencyMode.MAIN and the phone is already logged in or the phone/extension is already registered by your application or another application, and if the forceLogin parameter is true, your request for registration will supercede any previous registration. If the forceLogin parameter is false and all other conditions are the same, then your request for registration will fail, and the reason code in the RegisterTerminalResponse will be RegistrationConstants.EXTENSION_IN_USE.

    If registering with DependencyMode.INDEPENDENT or DependencyMode.DEPENDENT and the phone is already logged in or the phone/extension is already registered by your application or another application, your request for registration will not supercede any previous registration. Rather, the registering application will coexist with previous registrants. If the forceLogin parameter is false and the Communication Manager determines that the maximum number of registrants for an extension has already been reached, then your request for registration will fail. The reason code in the RegisterTerminalResponse will be RegistrationConstants.EXTENSION_IN_USE. If the forceLogin parameter is true and the maximum number of registrants has already been reached, then your request for registration will succeed, but previously registered applications will be immediately unregistered.

    Please note that media events are not available when the device is registered in MediaMode.NONE or MediaMode.TELECOMMUTER mode.

    Registration using RegistrationServices is a synchronous process and can take a relatively long time. Since the RegistrationServices.registerTerminal is a synchronous call, this request will block while waiting for a response. If it is desirable that the application thread be able to continue processing while waiting for the response, consider using AsynchronousServices (Java API only) to process the RegisterTerminalRequest.

    The RegisterTerminalRequest request has these parameters:

    RegisterTerminalRequest Parameters
    device Mandatory Unique identifier of phone/extension.
    loginInfo Mandatory Indicates the information necessary to login or register an extension with Communication Manager. See additional information in the next table.
    localMediaInfo Conditional If MediaMode.CLIENT is selected in the loginInfo parameter, then this parameter is mandatory and indicates where the Communication Manager should send the media stream, and which codecs, encryption, and packet size are preferred. Otherwise, this parameter is optional.

    The login information parameters are:

    LoginInfo Parameters
    e911 Optional Set to "block" to block E911 emergency call for telecommuter users.
    forceLogin Optional. Prior to release 4.0 of AE Services, this parameter was not supported, because login was always forced. Beginning with release 4.0 of AE Services, this flag is supported, and login will be forced only if the application requests it to be so.

    Defaults to false. Formerly, even if the phone was already logged in or the phone/extension was already registered by your application or another application, your request for registration would supercede any previous registration. Henceforth, if this parameter is not explicitly set to true, and Commmunication Manager determines that the maximum number of registrations for an extension has been reached, then the client will receive a RegisterTerminalResponse with the reason code set to RegistrationConstants.EXTENSION_IN_USE.
    sharedControl Deprecated Prior to release 4.0 of AE Services, this parameter was used to determine whether to register with shared control or exclusive control. It is no longer supported. The dependencyMode and mediaMode parameters of the loginInfo parameter should now be used to indicate the mode with which to register. A true value for this parameter corresponds to DependencyMode.DEPENDENT; a false value corresponds to DependencyMode.MAIN. Defaults to true.
    dependencyMode Mandatory The dependency mode with which to register. See DependencyMode for a description of these modes.
    mediaMode Mandatory The media mode with which to register. See MediaMode for a description of these modes.
    password Mandatory Password assigned to the station during station administration on Communication Manager.
    telecommuterExtension Conditional The telephone number of the real telephone that you are directing the media to. This parameter is mandatory when mediaMode is TELECOMMUTER; for any other media mode this parameter is prohibited.
    unicodeScript Optional This allows a DMCC device to receive unicode formatted display updates and button labels. This is intended for internationalization. The Communication Manager must be administered with proper unicode scripts for this feature to work.
    mediaContent Optional This allows a DMCC device to receive custom media stream from one of more parties in the call. See MediaContent for a description of available values. Defaults to FULL.
    mediaTonesAnnc Optional This allows a DMCC device to receive system generated tones and announcements in the media stream. It is of type boolean and defaults to true.

    The localMediaInfo parameter is of type MediaInfo.

    MediaInfo Parameters
    rtpAddress Conditional Specifies the Real Time Protocol address where the media should be directed. This parameter is mandatory when mediaMode is set to CLIENT; for any other media mode, this parameter is prohibited. The UDP port address should be an even number.
    rtcpAddress Conditional Specifies the Real Time Control Protocol address. This parameter is mandatory when mediaMode is set to CLIENT; for any other media mode, this parameter is prohibited. Specify the odd UDP port number that immediately follows the RTP port.
    codecs Optional The preferred set of codecs to be used for media coming to the device and media coming from the device. Possible values include:
    • MediaConstants.G711A (G.711 A-law)
    • MediaConstants.G711U (G.711 Mu-law)
    • MediaConstants.G729
    • MediaConstants.G729A
    • MediaConstants.G723
    Defaults to G.711 A-law and Mu-law, in that order. The G.723 codec may be used only for Client Media Mode (i.e. where the RTP stream is directed to a machine other than the CMAPI connector server and is handled by the application). Multiple codecs can be listed in preferential order. However, a mixture of G.711, G.729 and G.723 cannot be in the list (i.e., the list may contain one or more G.711 codecs or one or more G.729 codecs, but not a mixture of G.711 and G.729). Also, no conversion between G.711 and G.729 (or G.723) is provided by this API. To choose an appropriate codec set, you may wish to first determine how the device's network region and codecs are administered on Communication Manager. This set should consist of only codecs administered for the device's network region.
    encryption Optional Specifies a list of encryption algorithms supported for media (RTP). Possible values include:
    • MediaConstants.SRTP_AES128_HMAC80_ENC_AUTH
    • MediaConstants.SRTP_AES128_HMAC32_ENC_AUTH
    • MediaConstants.SRTP_AES128_HMAC80_ENC_UNAUTH
    • MediaConstants.SRTP_AES128_HMAC32_ENC_UNAUTH
    • MediaConstants.SRTP_AES128_HMAC80_UNENC_AUTH
    • MediaConstants.SRTP_AES128_HMAC32_UNENC_AUTH
    • MediaConstants.SRTP_AES128_HMAC80_UNENC_UNAUTH
    • MediaConstants.SRTP_AES128_HMAC32_UNENC_UNAUTH
    • MediaConstants.AES
    • MediaConstants.NOENCRYPTION
    This encryption list specifies the capabilities of the CMAPI endpoint. The actual algorithm that is chosen for a call is dependent on the administered list in Communication Manager. Administration of Media Encryption is done in the Communication Manager ip-codec-set form.
    packetSize Optional Specifies the size of media packets in milliseconds. Defaults to 20 milliseconds. Possible values are 10-60 in multiples of 10. Recommended to use default. If you don't use default, you must also administer Communication Manager to change the codec of the network region where the phone belongs.

    The following table describes the behavior and requirements of the media modes.

    Media ModesWhen to useWhat to set
    Server media mode Use if also using the Voice Unit Services. Media stream will terminate on connector server. Set the mediaMode parameter of loginInfo to MediaMode.SERVER. If you wish to use the default codecs and packet size, do not set local media info (let all local media info parameters default). If you want different codecs and/or packet size, then set the codecs and/or packet size, but do not set the RTP/RTCP address.
    Client media mode Use if media stream is to be processed by application. RTP stream can be terminated on any desired machine. Set the mediaMode parameter of loginInfo to MediaMode.CLIENT. Set local media info's RTP/RTCP address to desired IP address and port. May also set preferred codecs and/or preferred packet size. This is the only media mode in which redirectMedia is supported.
    Telecommuter media mode Use when an application wants the media to go to a real telephone. The real telephone can be inside or outside of the Communication Manager domain. Set the mediaMode parameter MediaMode.TELECOMMUTER, set the dependencyMode parameter to DependencyMode.MAIN, and set the telecommuterExtension of loginInfo to the telephone number of the real telephone to which you are directing the media.
    No media mode Use when an application only wants access to the signalling for an extension. Set the mediaMode parameter of loginInfo to MediaMode.NONE.

    The following table describes the behavior and requirements of the dependency modes.

    Dependency ModesWhen to useWhat to set
    Main mode Use this mode when you wish to be able to answer calls, make calls, talk, or listen, regardless of the presence of other registrants. There can be only one main registrant; once the main registrant exists, other registrants may register with the Communication Manager using the same extension only in dependent or independent mode. The main mode is similar to what was formerly called "exclusive control," except that it is now possible to use MediaMode.NONE to indicate that you desire to receive no media at all. Set the dependencyMode parameter of loginInfo to DependencyMode.MAIN.
    Dependent mode Use this mode when you wish registration to succeed only if a main registrant already exists and you only require the ability to listen to a call. Combined with MediaMode.NONE, dependent mode is equivalent to what was formerly called "shared control" mode. Set the dependencyMode parameter of loginInfo to DependencyMode.DEPENDENT.
    Independent mode Use this mode when you wish registration to succeed regardless of whether a main registrant already exists. If a main registrant does not already exist when you register in independent mode, then your application may answer calls, make calls, talk, or listen until a main registrant appears.

    Independent mode can be useful when, to achieve high availability, two instances of an application register on an extension that doesn't have an associated end-user telephone. One would register in main mode and the other in independent mode. In this case the Communication Manager would will allow either registrant to answer calls, make calls, talk, or listen, immediately after they register.

    		Set the dependencyMode parameter of loginInfo to DependencyMode.INDEPENDENT.

    The RegisterTerminalResponse indicates the outcome of the request.

    If your application will control the media stream, then it will also need to monitor the media events. The Media Events that may be caused by a RegisterTerminalRequest request include:

    • MediaStartEvent
    • MediaStopEvent

    Negative Acknowledgements:

    • operation:invalidDeviceID - Sent if there is no station associated with the DeviceID or the format of DeviceID is not correct
    • stateIncompatibility:invalidActiveDeviceState - Sent if the station is in the process of registering or unregistering
    • operation:invalidParameterValue - Sent if the password is NULL or the request is NULL or there is an invalid codec or invalid encryption specified.
    • stateIncompatibility:invalidDeviceState - Sent if the device is already registered.
    • operation:parameterNotSupported - Sent if unsupported parameters are used.
    • operation:generic - Sent if there is an operation error such as a socket IO error.
    • unspecified - Sent if the request parameter is null or if an implementation-specific error occurs.

      • getLocalMediaInfo

        public MediaInfo getLocalMediaInfo()
        Returns the value of field 'localMediaInfo'. The field 'localMediaInfo' has the following description: The localMediaInfo specifies the client-side media info. That is, the client has the option to specify its (the client's) media info at registration time. If the mediaMode parameter is set to MediaMode.CLIENT, then all of the parameters of localMediaInfo must be provided by the application. If the mediaMode parameter is set to MediaMode.Server, then the server will provide its own RTP/RTCP address and port parameters; if you wish to provide codec, encryption, or packet size parameters, the server will accept them.

        Note: The packet size parameter is just a recommendation for the server. the actual packet size used will depend on CM administration.

        Returns:
        MediaInfo
